How Spark uses Scala — what to expect when you read its source.

Apache Spark itself is written in Scala. When you eventually crack open the Spark source, there are five shapes you will see over and over. None of them will be a surprise by the end of this track.

You will see a case class used as the in-memory representation of one record. That is an immutable data record with an auto-generated equals, hash code, to-string, and pattern-matching support. Notebook five covers case classes.

You will see a dataframe filter passed a short lambda that checks one field — a function passed where a function of one argument is expected. Functions as values. That is notebook three.

You will see a sealed trait followed by a handful of case objects extending it — say, an inner join, a left outer join, and so on. That is an algebraic data type, a closed set of subtypes the compiler can check exhaustively in a match expression. Notebooks five and six.

You will see an implicit value of some encoder type — that is a type-class instance. The Scala 2 syntax uses the implicit keyword; Scala 3 uses given. Same idea, cleaner keyword. Notebook eight.

And you will see a future wrapping an expensive computation, then chained with map — an asynchronous result composed without blocking. Notebook nine.

One last thing. Spark still uses brace syntax and Scala 2 point 13 throughout. The constructs are identical; only the surface syntax differs. You will not be reading unfamiliar territory — you will be reading the same language, with curly braces and an older keyword for given.
